Thus while the random network (r = 1) converges quickest, the small-world  network (r = 0.05) also shows a substantial improvement over the tight communities represented by the one-dimensional ring lattice.
Moreover, this result might be even stronger in reality if agents in poorly-connected  networks attempt to compensate for the relative sparcity of connections by making more forceful or persuasive referrals where they do occur.
